Hi John,



What hardware does a crawler instance run on and what is your Internet b/w?
385M/3m from a single crawler instance is very impressive.



- leo



  _____  

From: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
[mailto:archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of lekash
Sent: Friday, June 06, 2008 1:21 PM
To: archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
Subject: Re: [archive-crawler] Crawling 100 million pages



Hi there,

I&#39;m like to very much encourage being careful about &#39;speeding up heritrix&#39;.
Politeness is really important on the net. I keep doubling my inter 
crawl delay every
year, and still people have problems. 

Its not a heretrix limit you will be looking at. Its a hardware 
capacity limit.
(Though the most I&#39;ve gotten a single crawler to do is
385M over a three month period.)
A crawler group, I&#39;ve gotten to 6B /year.
So, 100 M /month is well within the operating range.

The 1.x crawler seems to have a limit around 680M for a single crawler,
like the queued numbers stop going up then. Never got there, so don&#39;t
know what would happen. I haven&#39;t run a multi-billion one on the 2.x line,
maybe next year.

The things that run out of space are memory for java heap space, and
something funny with the database. Re-writing scratch files in that
seems to be what slows it down later, despite a still wide frontier.

And of course, urls are not a consistent measure, as size varies widely.
e.g. .gov sites are 10 times as dense in text/pdf as .com sites,
and .com sites have all the visuals and movies. Depends on what
you are crawling.

John

